      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n720:         </div>\n721: \n722:         <!-- GLOSSARY ENTRIES -->\n723: \n724:         <div id=\"gloss-A\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">\n725:             <h3 style=\"font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:16px; color:var(--accent);\">A</h3>\n726: \n727:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n728:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">accent gradient</div>\n729:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n730:                 <strong>Why \"accent\" not \"secondary\", \"highlight\", or \"pop colour\":</strong> In design-token systems, \"accent\" is the\n731:                 industry-standard term for the colour that provides visual emphasis against a dominant \"base\" or \"primary\". \n732:                 \"Secondary\" implies a supporting role for information, not emphasis. \"Highlight\" is reserved for UI selection states. \n733:                 \"Pop colour\" is colloquial and not machine-parseable in token pipelines. \"Accent\" is neutral, precise, and maps\n734:                 directly to CSS variables (<code>--accent</code>), design tool colour styles, and component props.\n735:                 </p>\n736:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n737:                 <strong>The gradient is copper-to-crimson (#c08060 → #c04060). Why a gradient, not a flat colour:</strong> A flat accent\n738:                 colour would make the continent read as a solid shape rather than a luminous, energetic form. The gradient simulates\n739:                 a light source moving diagonally (135°) across the surface, creating depth and a subtle \"glow\" that evokes fire, embers,\n740:                 and the warmth of the African continent. Flat colour would feel static and vector-like — appropriate for a tech logo\n741:                 but wrong for an Afro-dance organisation that wants to convey energy, movement, and passion.\n742:                 </p>\n743:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n744:                 <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) The gradient creates visual depth without requiring a separate shadow or highlight\n745:                 layer, keeping the file small. (2) It encodes brand emotion — copper = earth/heritage, crimson = energy/passion —\n746:                 in a single visual property. (3) It works across media: on screens the gradient animates subtly, in print it\n747:                 reproduces as a rich tonal range, on merchandise it can be replaced with foil stamping. (4) The specific angle\n748:                 (135°) and stops (20% copper → 50% amber → 100% crimson) are tuneable tokens that a developer can adjust in\n749:                 one place: <code>--accent-gradient: linear-gradient(135deg, #c08060 20%, #c0a040 50%, #c04060 100%)</code>.\n750:                 </p>\n751:             </div>\n752: \n753:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n754:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">acronym (\"AFJ\")</div>\n755:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n756:                 <strong>Why \"acronym\" not \"initials\", \"abbreviation\", or \"logo mark\":</strong> \"AFJ\" stands for \"African and FunJive\" (the\n757:                 full registered name of the organisation). It is pronounced as three separate letters (/eɪ/ /ɛf/ /dʒeɪ/), making it\n758:                 an acronym rather than an initialism (where each letter sounds independently). In design, calling it an \"acronym\" \n759:                 signals that the letters represent expanded words, not standalone symbols. \"Logo mark\" would be confusing because\n760:                 the continent shape is the mark — the acronym is specifically the <em>textual identifier</em>.\n761:                 </p>\n762:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n763:                 <strong>Why it exists:</strong> The acronym is the single most recognisable identifier for AFJ Cardiff — dancers,\n764:                 students, and social-media followers all refer to the organisation as \"AFJ\" (never \"African and FunJive\"). It\n765:                 serves as the primary verbal hook and visual anchor.\n766:                 </p>\n767:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n768:                 <strong>What it helps with:</strong> (1) Searchability — \"AFJ Cardiff\" is short enough for Instagram handles,\n769:                 hashtags, and URLs (afjcardiff.com). (2) Memorability — three letters are easier to recall than a full phrase,\n770:                 especially across languages. (3) Brand protection — the acronym can be trademarked as a word mark, providing\n771:                 legal coverage beyond the full name.\n772:                 </p>\n773:             </div>\n774: \n775:             <div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n776:                 <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">African continent silhouette (primary element)</div>\n777:                 <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n778:                 <strong>Why \"silhouette\" not \"outline\", \"shape\", \"map\", or \"icon\":</strong> \"Silhouette\" specifically means a filled\n779:                 shape with no internal detail — the continent is rendered as a solid form with a gradient fill, not a stroked\n\n(Showing lines 720-779 of 2593. Use offset=780 to continue.)\n</content>",
