    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "grep",
      "code": "{\"include\": \"logo_deconstruction.html\", \"pattern\": \"ADR|adr\", \"path\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\"}",
      "output": "Found 59 matches\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html:\n  Line 79: details.collapse.adr-item { margin-bottom: 20px; padding: 0; }\r\n\n  Line 80: details.collapse.adr-item > summary {\r\n\n  Line 88: details.collapse.adr-item[open] > summary {\r\n\n  Line 91: details.collapse.adr-item > .collapse-body {\r\n\n  Line 94: details.collapse.adr-item .status-badge {\r\n\n  Line 104: details.collapse.adr-item .status-badge .accepted { color: var(--green); }\r\n\n  Line 1974: <!-- 8. Architectural Decision Records (ADR) -->\r\n\n  Line 1979:     Every design decision in the AFJ Cardiff logo is recorded below as an Architectural Decision Record (ADR) — \r\n\n  Line 1981:     Thoughtworks Technology Advisory Board). Each ADR captures: the <strong>context</strong> that required a decision, \r\n\n  Line 1984:     ADRs ensure future designers, developers, and stakeholders understand <em>why</em> the logo is the way it is — \r\n\n  Line 1988:     <!-- ADR-001 -->\r\n\n  Line 1991:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-001 &mdash; Canvas Dimensions &amp; Near-Square Format</div>\r\n\n  Line 2020:     <!-- ADR-002 -->\r\n\n  Line 2023:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-002 &mdash; African Continent Silhouette as Primary Visual Element</div>\r\n\n  Line 2047:     <!-- ADR-003 -->\r\n\n  Line 2050:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-003 &mdash; Copper-to-Crimson Warm Gradient Over Flat Colour</div>\r\n\n  Line 2074:     <!-- ADR-004 -->\r\n\n  Line 2077:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-004 &mdash; Black Base Background Over White or Transparent</div>\r\n\n  Line 2092:             <strong>Dark grey (#1a1a1a) or navy (#202040):</strong> Considered but rejected — pure black provides the maximum contrast for the warm gradient. Any lighter background would reduce the perceived brilliance of copper, amber, and crimson. Navy was reserved for the classroom UI palette (ADR-010).</p>\r\n\n  Line 2100:     <!-- ADR-005 - AFJ Acronym -->\r\n\n  Line 2103:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-005 &mdash; \"AFJ\" Acronym at Top in Bold Sans-Serif (Primary Typography)</div>\r\n\n  Line 2124:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The font must be either a commercially licensed sans-serif typeface (e.g., Montserrat, Space Grotesk, Inter, Helvetica Now) or a free-academic-use face. The specific font choice is documented separately from this ADR (it may change if the licence expires). (2) In contexts where the acronym alone is used without the full logo (e.g., Instagram bio \"AFJ Cardiff\"), the brand still works because \"AFJ\" is recognisable. (3) New audiences may not immediately know what \"AFJ\" stands for — this is intentional: they are invited to discover the full name on the website. (4) The tight kerning may cause legibility issues at very small sizes (< 16px) — the \"A\" and \"F\" may appear to touch on low-resolution screens.</p>\r\n\n  Line 2128:     <!-- ADR-006 - CARDIFF Wordmark -->\r\n\n  Line 2131:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-006 &mdash; \"CARDIFF\" Wordmark — All-Caps, Smaller, Below Continent</div>\r\n\n  Line 2157:             <strong>Horizontal layout (\"AFJ CARDIFF\" on one line):</strong> Rejected — a horizontal wordmark would make the logo wider than square, breaking the near-square format (ADR-001). Horizontal lockups also read as \"AFJ CARDIFF [continent]\" which reverses the intended narrative order (name → continent → location).<br>\r\n\n  Line 2162:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If AFJ Cardiff expands to other cities (e.g., \"AFJ Swansea\", \"AFJ Bristol\"), new logos must be produced with the same lockup structure but different wordmarks. Each city variant needs its own ADR. (2) The small \"CARDIFF\" text may be illegible at very small sizes (< 30px total logo height) — for app icons and favicons, the wordmark may need to be dropped, using only \"AFJ\" + continent. (3) \"Cardiff\" in all-caps (7 letters, all uppercase) increases character recognition time by ~10% compared to title case (studies show all-caps text is read more slowly for word-length text) — but for a 7-letter wordmark that functions as a visual identifier, not reading text, this trade-off is acceptable. (4) The all-caps \"CARDIFF\" is a registered part of the brand mark — it cannot be set in lower case or title case in official materials without approval.</p>\r\n\n  Line 2174:     <!-- ADR-007 - Asymmetric Margins -->\r\n\n  Line 2177:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-007 &mdash; Asymmetric Margin Distribution</div>\r\n\n  Line 2190:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Symmetric margins (25% each side):</strong> Rejected — perfect symmetry would make the logo feel static and formal. The 44px leftward content offset (ADR-011) would make symmetric margins look \"off-centre\" rather than intentionally weighted. Asymmetry signals the logo is dynamic, not a passive corporate seal.<br>\r\n\n  Line 2196:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If the logo is cropped for square usage (Instagram profile), the right 9% and bottom 5.4% extra margins mean a square crop will cut unevenly — more from right/bottom than left/top. This is acceptable because the content is already shifted left/up (ADR-011), so a square crop actually brings the content closer to visual centre. (2) The asymmetric margins are a brand signal: they communicate that AFJ Cardiff is \"intentionally off-centre\" — dynamic, unconventional, organic. This reinforces the dance organisation's identity (movement, rhythm, asymmetry in body positions) versus a static corporate brand.</p>\r\n\n  Line 2200:     <!-- ADR-008 -->\r\n\n  Line 2203:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-008 &mdash; Warm Earth-and-Fire Palette Over Cool or Neutral</div>\r\n\n  Line 2227:     <!-- ADR-009 -->\r\n\n  Line 2230:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-009 &mdash; Same Gradient on Text and Continent for Visual Unity</div>\r\n\n  Line 2253:     <!-- ADR-010 -->\r\n\n  Line 2256:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-010 &mdash; Dual Colour System (Warm Brand Identity + Cool Classroom UI)</div>\r\n\n  Line 2275:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) All AFJ Cardiff materials must specify which palette they belong to — a marketing poster cannot accidentally use classroom navy for the main background (it would look like an educational document) and a classroom worksheet cannot use the warm palette for body text (reduced readability). (2) The dual system requires documentation and governance — a \"brand palette vs UI palette\" decision tree must be created so content creators choose the right palette automatically. (3) When the warm logo is placed on the navy classroom background (which happens in the classroom portal header), the complementary contrast makes the logo \"pop\" dramatically — this is not a bug but a feature of the dual system (ADR-010 describes the ~190° hue separation that creates this effect).</p>\r\n\n  Line 2279:     <!-- ADR-011 -->\r\n\n  Line 2282:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-011 &mdash; Content Offset 44px Left of Canvas Centre</div>\r\n\n  Line 2304:     <!-- ADR-012 -->\r\n\n  Line 2307:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-012 &mdash; 216 DPI Resolution</div>\r\n\n  Line 2330:     <!-- ADR-013 -->\r\n\n  Line 2333:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-013 &mdash; No Alpha Channel (Opaque Black) Over Transparency</div>\r\n\n  Line 2346:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Transparent background (alpha channel):</strong> Rejected — see ADR-004 for the full rationale. In summary, the warm gradient requires a dark background for sufficient contrast; transparency would expose the logo to light backgrounds which destroy the \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect. A transparent variant (new ADR) could be created for light-background contexts.<br>\r\n\n  Line 2347:             <strong>White background:</strong> Rejected — see ADR-004. White would eliminate the dramatic contrast that defines the logo's visual identity.</p>\r\n\n  Line 2355:     <!-- ADR-014 -->\r\n\n  Line 2358:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-014 &mdash; Bold Sans-Serif Typeface Over Serif, Script, or Display</div>\r\n\n  Line 2367:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>bold weight (700–800) sans-serif</strong> typeface — likely a geometric or neo-grotesque sans-serif with clean lines, consistent stroke widths, and open counters (e.g., Space Grotesk, Montserrat, Inter, Helvetica Now, or Univers — the specific face requires font-matching analysis from the bitmap). The choice of \"sans-serif\" over other categories was definitive; the specific font family within sans-serif is a secondary ADR (ADR-014a).</p>\r\n\n  Line 2378:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The specific sans-serif font must be identified and licensed. If it is a free Google Font (Montserrat, Space Grotesk, Inter), the logo can be used by anyone without font-licence concerns. If it is a paid font (Helvetica Now, Univers), all materials using the logo must have the appropriate font licence. (2) The font's bold weight (700–800) is critical — if another weight is accidentally substituted (e.g., Regular 400), the acronym will look weak and disproportional to the continent. (3) For body text and supporting materials (not the logo itself), a complementary sans-serif (perhaps the same family at a lighter weight, or a different family) should be chosen with an appropriate x-height match — this is a separate ADR (Typography Pairing).</p>\r\n\n  Line 2382:     <!-- ADR-015 -->\r\n\n  Line 2385:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-015 &mdash; Tight Kerning for \"AFJ\" Acronym Over Default Letter Spacing</div>\r\n\n  Line 2399:             <strong>Loose tracking (more space):</strong> Rejected — widely-spaced letters would look formal and luxurious (like a fashion brand logo: \"A · F · J\"), which contradicts the energetic, immediate, community-focused brand. Loose tracking also requires more horizontal space, which conflicts with the near-square canvas (ADR-001).<br>\r\n\n  Line 2413:     <!-- ADR Summary -->\r\n\n  Line 2415:         <h3 style=\"font-size:1rem; font-weight:600; margin-bottom:12px; color:var(--accent);\">ADR Summary</h3>\r\n\n  Line 2417:             <strong>15 Architectural Decision Records</strong> document all design decisions for the AFJ Cardiff logo. Every ADR follows the same structure: Context → Decision → Alternatives Considered (with rejection rationale) → Consequences (trade-offs, constraints, downstream effects). \r\n\n  Line 2420:             The ADR approach is borrowed from software engineering (Michael Nygard, 2011) and adapted for design decisions. Key principles: (1) Decisions are documented <em>before</em> they are forgotten — not retroactively. (2) Alternatives are listed with specific rejection reasons, not just \"considered\". (3) Consequences include both positive and negative outcomes. (4) ADRs are living documents — if a decision is reversed or modified, a new ADR supersedes the old one (with Status: Superseded).\r\n\n  Line 2438: img.src = 'data:image/png;base64,...\n  Line 2575:             img.src = 'data:image/png;base64,...\n  Line 2585:         img.src = 'data:image/png;base64,...",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1781576393020
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\logo_deconstruction.html\", \"offset\": 2000, \"limit\": 100}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\logo_deconstruction.html</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n2000:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">Canvas set to <strong>974 × 992 pixels</strong>, aspect ratio <strong>487:496</strong> (0.9819). This is 1.8% taller than wide — as close to square as possible while preserving each element's natural proportions. The content bounding box (468×462) occupies only 22.7% of canvas area, leaving generous margins.</p>\n2001:         </div>\n2002:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2003:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2004:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Perfect square (1:1):</strong> Rejected — the continent silhouette's natural shape and the vertical text stack create a taller composition. Forcing 1:1 would require cropping the top of \"AFJ\" or bottom of \"CARDIFF\", which destroys the lockup.<br>\n2005:             <strong>Landscape rectangle (16:9 or 4:3):</strong> Rejected — horizontal logos are common in tech but look wrong for social-media profile pictures, favicons, and app icons, all of which use square frames.<br>\n2006:             <strong>Standard SVG artboard sizes:</strong> Rejected — design software defaults do not align with the content's natural proportions. The designer let the content dictate the canvas size, not the other way around.</p>\n2007:         </div>\n2008:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2009:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2010:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) If this logo is displayed in a square image slot (Instagram profile, favicon), 1.8% of the height will be cropped — a negligible loss that removes only background, not content. (2) Developers resizing the logo must preserve aspect ratio: use <code>width: auto; height: 100%</code> or specify <code>aspect-ratio: 487/496</code> in CSS. (3) The canvas is not standard (e.g., 1024×1024), which means design tools may not have a preset — the custom size must be entered manually. (4) Printing at 216 DPI yields ~4.51\" × 4.59\" physical size — fits standard 5\" × 5\" badge frames but not perfectly centred.</p>\n2011:         </div>\n2012:         <div>\n2013:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Token Reference</div>\n2014:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">canvas.width</span><span class=\"value\">974px</span><span class=\"desc\">drives all proportional calculations</span></div>\n2015:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">canvas.height</span><span class=\"value\">992px</span><span class=\"desc\">drives all proportional calculations</span></div>\n2016:             <div class=\"token-row\"><span class=\"token\">aspect.ratio</span><span class=\"value\">0.9819</span><span class=\"desc\">487:496 — critical for responsive scaling</span></div>\n2017:         </div>\n2018:     </div>\n2019: \n2020:     <!-- ADR-002 -->\n2021:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2022:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2023:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-002 &mdash; African Continent Silhouette as Primary Visual Element</div>\n2024:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2025:         </div>\n2026:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2027:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2028:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo required a pictorial mark that communicates \"African heritage\" instantly, without requiring text. This mark would serve as the primary recognisable element in contexts where text is too small to read (favicons, social-media avatars, merchandise tags) and as the emotional anchor of the brand identity.</p>\n2029:         </div>\n2030:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2031:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2032:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The <strong>African continent silhouette</strong> fills 468×462px (22.7% of canvas) centred at x=209, y=238. It is rendered as a solid filled shape (not a stroked outline) with a warm copper-to-crimson gradient, creating a \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect. The silhouette is abstracted — it is a recognisable continent shape but does not include internal borders, labels, or geographic detail.</p>\n2033:         </div>\n2034:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2035:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2036:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Map with internal borders:</strong> Rejected — adding country borders inside the continent would make the silhouette too complex, raising edge density above 1.5% and breaking the minimalist aesthetic. It would also imply political endorsement of specific borders, which is unwise for an inclusive dance organisation serving diaspora communities from many African nations.<br>\n2037:             <strong>Pan-African colours (red, gold, green):</strong> Rejected — the Pan-African palette is used by many organisations (including political parties) and would be hard to own. The warm copper-crimson palette is unique to AFJ Cardiff and avoids conflation with any political movement.<br>\n2038:             <strong>Abstract shape (circles, waves, geometric):</strong> Rejected — abstract shapes cannot communicate \"African heritage\" explicitly. The continent silhouette is unambiguous and requires no cultural knowledge to decode.<br>\n2039:             <strong>Dancer silhouette as primary:</strong> Rejected — dancer silhouettes are generic (could be any dance company). The continent grounds the brand specifically in African dance.</p>\n2040:         </div>\n2041:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2042:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2043:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The continent silhouette must be treated as a sacred brand element — it cannot be rotated, squished, recoloured to non-warm colours, or replaced. (2) At very small sizes (< 20px), the continent outline may lose detail — a simplified icon variant may be needed for favicons. (3) The silhouette creates a strong \"Africa first\" brand positioning — this may alienate non-African audiences if not balanced with inclusive messaging in surrounding content. (4) The continent outline's anti-aliasing produces ~7,955 intermediate colours — expected and acceptable for a smooth gradient edge.</p>\n2044:         </div>\n2045:     </div>\n2046: \n2047:     <!-- ADR-003 -->\n2048:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2049:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2050:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-003 &mdash; Copper-to-Crimson Warm Gradient Over Flat Colour</div>\n2051:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2052:         </div>\n2053:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2054:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2055:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The continent silhouette and typography needed a fill that communicates energy, warmth, and African cultural heritage. A single flat colour would be clean but static — insufficient to evoke the \"fire, earth, and passion\" of Afro dance. The fill had to work on a black background, reproduce in print, and translate to merchandise (embroidery, screen printing, foil stamping).</p>\n2056:         </div>\n2057:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2058:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2059:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">A <strong>linear gradient at 135°</strong> with 3 stops: copper/bronze (#c08060) at 20%, amber/gold (#c0a040) at 50%, and crimson/rose (#c04060) at 100%. This creates a diagonal \"fire sweep\" across the continent — the brightest gold at upper-left (where the eye enters), transitioning through warm copper to deep crimson at lower-right. The gradient occupies ~7.6% of total canvas pixels.</p>\n2060:         </div>\n2061:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2062:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2063:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Flat single colour (e.g., solid gold #d4af37):</strong> Rejected — flat colour lacks depth. The continent would appear as a solid cutout rather than a luminous form. Flat gold also reads as \"luxury\" not \"dance energy\", which is the wrong brand emotion.<br>\n2064:             <strong>Radial gradient (centre-out):</strong> Rejected — a radial gradient would make the continent look like a spotlight effect, which is self-conscious and unnatural. Linear at 135° mimics natural sunlight from upper-left, the standard lighting convention in Western and African visual art.<br>\n2065:             <strong>Multiple separate colours for different areas:</strong> Rejected — the continent silhouette is a single shape; breaking it into colour zones would make it look like a patchwork or puzzle, losing the silhouette's iconic clarity.<br>\n2066:             <strong>Rainbow/multi-colour:</strong> Rejected — too complex for a minimalist logo, hard to reproduce in print, and visually exhausting.</p>\n2067:         </div>\n2068:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2069:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2070:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The gradient cannot be perfectly reproduced in screen printing (which uses solid ink colours) — for merchandise, the gradient must be converted to a 2-colour or 3-colour simulated process, or replaced with a metallic foil stamp. (2) For embroidery, the gradient must be approximated with thread colour stepping (copper → amber → crimson in concentric zones). (3) On e‑ink displays (e‑readers, some price tags), the gradient degrades to greyscale — the contrast remains but the emotional \"warmth\" is lost. (4) The 135° angle should be preserved when exporting for web (CSS <code>linear-gradient(135deg, ...)</code>) but may need adjustment for specific layout contexts (e.g., 45° for right-aligned logos).</p>\n2071:         </div>\n2072:     </div>\n2073: \n2074:     <!-- ADR-004 -->\n2075:     <div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n2076:         <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n2077:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-004 &mdash; Black Base Background Over White or Transparent</div>\n2078:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n2079:         </div>\n2080:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2081:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n2082:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo needed a background colour (or transparency) for its canvas. The choice affects contrast with the warm gradient, versatility across different media (white paper, dark websites, merchandise), file size, and print cost.</p>\n2083:         </div>\n2084:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2085:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n2086:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Pure black (#000000) opaque background, covering 92.1% of the canvas.</strong> The logo PNG has <strong>no alpha channel</strong> (no transparency). The black background is an integral part of the design, not a default canvas colour. Every logo usage must either place it on a black background or accept the black rectangle as a visible border.</p>\n2087:         </div>\n2088:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2089:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Alternatives Considered</div>\n2090:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\"><strong>Transparent background (alpha channel):</strong> Rejected — on a white background (common in printed materials, many websites), the warm gradient would have contrast ratio of only ~3.5:1 against white — insufficient for visual pop. The \"fire-and-earth glow\" effect requires a dark backdrop for the warm colours to luminesce. Transparency would also increase file size (alpha channel adds ~15% to PNG size).<br>\n2091:             <strong>White background (#ffffff):</strong> Rejected — white backgrounds are the default in most corporate branding, which would make AFJ Cardiff look like a conventional business rather than a creative arts organisation. Black creates immediate differentiation and signals premium/cultural/nighttime/dance-club energy.<br>\n2092:             <strong>Dark grey (#1a1a1a) or navy (#202040):</strong> Considered but rejected — pure black provides the maximum contrast for the warm gradient. Any lighter background would reduce the perceived brilliance of copper, amber, and crimson. Navy was reserved for the classroom UI palette (ADR-010).</p>\n2093:         </div>\n2094:         <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n2095:             <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Consequences</div>\n2096:             <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">(1) The logo <strong>cannot</strong> be placed on a white or light background without creating a harsh black rectangle. If used on a white website header, the logo must have <code>background: #000</code> and the header must accommodate a black block. (2) For merchandise (t-shirts, hoodies), the solid black background means the print shop screens only the warm gradient area — the black becomes the garment colour (if the garment is black) or must be printed as an underbase (if the garment is white/coloured). (3) For social media profile pictures, the black background outside a circular crop is visible — the crop must be the full square, not trimmed to the continent. (4) <strong>Positive consequence:</strong> the black coverage (92.1%) compresses extremely efficiently in PNG — a 3MB raw bitmap becomes 65KB, a 47:1 compression ratio, because large uniform black areas are encoded as short run-lengths.</p>\n2097:         </div>\n2098:     </div>\n2099: \n\n(Showing lines 2000-2099 of 2593. Use offset=2100 to continue.)\n</content>",
