      "text": "Here are the findings:\n\n**1. `<details class=\"collapse glossary-item\">` count: 0**\nNo `<details>` elements exist anywhere in the file. The CSS defines styling for `details.collapse.glossary-item` (lines 64–78) and `details.collapse.adr-item` (lines 79–104), but the HTML never uses them.\n\n**2. `<details class=\"collapse adr-item\">` count: 0**\nSame as above — the ADR entries are plain `<div>` elements with inline styles.\n\n**3. Letter heading groups as `<details>`? No**\nThey are `<div id=\"gloss-X\" style=\"margin-bottom:32px;\">` containers with an `<h3>` heading — not collapsible `<details>` elements.\n\n**4. First glossary entry** (starts at line 727, 5 lines after `<!-- GLOSSARY ENTRIES -->` at line 722):\n```html\n<div style=\"background:var(--surface2); border-radius:8px; padding:16px; margin-bottom:16px; border-left:3px solid var(--accent);\">\n    <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--accent); font-weight:600; margin-bottom:4px;\">accent gradient</div>\n    <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n    <strong>Why \"accent\" not \"secondary\", \"highlight\", or \"pop colour\":</strong> In design-token systems, \"accent\" is the ...\n    </p>\n    <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7; margin-bottom:8px;\">\n    <strong>The gradient is copper-to-crimson (#c08060 → #c04060). Why a gradient, not a flat colour:</strong> ...\n    </p>\n    <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">\n    <strong>What it enables:</strong> (1) The gradient creates visual depth ...\n    </p>\n</div>\n```\n\n**5. First ADR entry — ADR-001** (starts at line 1988):\n```html\n<div style=\"background:var(--surface); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:12px; padding:24px; margin-bottom:20px;\">\n    <div style=\"display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; margin-bottom:16px; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px;\">\n        <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:600; color:var(--accent);\">ADR-001 — Canvas Dimensions & Near-Square Format</div>\n        <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.7rem; color:var(--text-dim); background:var(--surface2); padding:3px 10px; border-radius:20px; border:1px solid var(--border);\">Status: <span style=\"color:var(--green);\">Accepted</span></div>\n    </div>\n    <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n        <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Context</div>\n        <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">The logo canvas needed dimensions ...</p>\n    </div>\n    <div style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">\n        <div style=\"font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.75rem; color:var(--text-dim); text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:1px; margin-bottom:4px;\">Decision</div>\n        <p style=\"font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--text-dim); line-height:1.7;\">Canvas set to <strong>974 × 992 pixels</strong> ...</p>\n    </div>\n    ...\n</div>\n```\n\n**Bottom line: The transformation to `<details class=\"collapse glossary-item\">` / `<details class=\"collapse adr-item\">` has NOT been applied.** The CSS is ready (lists entry styles for those selectors), but the HTML still uses `<div>` elements with inline styles — no collapsible behavior exists. The glossary entries and ADR entries are all static `<div>` blocks.",
